## Commands

All commands run from the repo root unless noted. `<<RUNTIME>>` must be on
PATH.

```bash
bun install                   # install dependencies
bun test                      # run all tests
bun test <path/to/file>       # run a single test file
bun run lint                  # biome check --error-on-warnings .
bun run typecheck             # tsc --noEmit
bun run check:all             # full quality-gate suite (see below)
bun run check:coverage        # tests + coverage ratchet
bun run test:ci               # bun test with junit + coverage reporters
bun run report:test-timing    # slowest suites/tests from junit.xml
bun run report:quality-metrics # consolidated quality summary
```

If `<<REPO_NAME>>` ships a CLI, also document the user-facing entry point:

```bash
<<PRIMARY_CLI>> --help        # CLI top-level help
<<PRIMARY_CLI>> <subcommand>  # the most-used subcommand
```

### Quality gates

`bun run check:all` chains every gate CI also enforces:

- `check:size` — `scripts/check-file-sizes.ts` (line-count ratchet)
- `check:debt` — `scripts/check-debt-markers.ts` (tracker-pinned TODOs)
- `check:dups` — `bunx jscpd` (duplicate-code detector)
- `check:deps` — `knip --dependencies` (unused / undeclared deps)
- `check:agents` — `scripts/validate-agents-md.ts` (this file's references)
- `check:coverage` — `scripts/check-coverage.ts` (per-package floors)

Each script reads a JSON budget under `scripts/`. Budgets ratchet in one
direction only (file-size and debt-markers tighten downward; coverage
tightens upward). Do not loosen a budget without filing
`<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX` and noting it in the commit body.

## Conventions

### Filenames & directories

- Source files: `kebab-case.ts`. Tests are `<name>.test.ts` next to the
  file under test.
- Directories: `kebab-case`.
- React components (if any): `PascalCase.tsx`.
- TOML / YAML config keys stay `snake_case` to match upstream schemas.

Enforced by Biome's `style.useFilenamingConvention` rule (strict
kebab-case) in `biome.json`.

### Identifiers

- `camelCase` for functions, variables, instance fields.
- `PascalCase` for types, interfaces, classes, React components.
- `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` for module-level constants that are true constants.
- Booleans read as predicates: `isOpen`, `hasPreview`.

### TypeScript

- Strict mode with `noUncheckedIndexedAccess` — always handle possible
  `undefined` from indexing.
- No `any`; use `unknown` and narrow.
- Import with `.ts` extensions.
- Tab indentation, 100-char line width (Biome enforces).

### Test naming

- `describe("<unitUnderTest>")` + `test("verb-led behaviour description")`.
- No `should`, no `it`.

### Debt markers

Every `TODO` / `FIXME` / `HACK` / `XXX` on a source line must carry a
tracker reference on the same line. Accepted prefixes:

- `<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX` — repo-local tracker
- `mx-XXXX` — cross-repo mission tracker
- `#NNN` — GitHub issue
- A URL (any http link) — external reference

`scripts/check-debt-markers.ts` fails CI on bare markers.

### Log scrubbing

Any structured logger in `<<REPO_NAME>>` must redact sensitive keys
(`token`, `api_key`, `password`, `secret`, `authorization`,
`set-cookie`). Add new redact paths in the same commit that introduces a
new sensitive field.

## Agent Workflow

When an agent works in `<<REPO_NAME>>`, it should:

1. **Prime context.** Read this file (`AGENTS.md`), `<<UPSTREAM_DOCS>>` if
   present, and the most recent CHANGELOG entry to learn the current
   release cadence.
2. **Find unblocked work.** Use the repo's issue tracker (Seeds:
   `sd ready`; GitHub: `gh issue list`).
3. **Make focused changes.** One concern per commit. Preserve existing
   conventions — adapt, don't overwrite.
4. **Run gates locally.** `bun run lint && bun run typecheck && bun test &&
   bun run check:all` must all exit 0 before commit.
5. **Pin debt markers.** Any new `TODO` / `FIXME` must reference a tracker
   id created in the same change.
6. **Commit & sync.** Commit message follows
   `<area>: <summary>` (e.g. `quality: ratchet file-size cap`).
7. **Record insights.** If the project uses Mulch, `ml record` any
   convention discovered or failure encountered.

### Session completion protocol

Before ending a session:

1. File issues for remaining work.
2. Run `bun run check:all`.
3. Close finished issues.
4. Record session insights (Mulch / equivalent).
5. Push only when the user requests it; otherwise leave commits local.
6. Verify `git status` is clean.

## Testing & Validation Guidance

### Per-change verification

After every code change (before commit):

```bash
bun run lint
bun run typecheck
bun test
bun run check:all
```

All four must exit 0. CI runs the same four — local greens are the
contract.

### Coverage discipline

`bun run check:coverage` enforces `scripts/coverage-budgets.json`.
The ratchet only goes **up**. Raising a floor when coverage improves is
encouraged; lowering one requires a `<<TRACKER_PREFIX>>-XXXX` in the
commit body explaining what tests were removed and why.

### Tests live under `<<TEST_ROOT>>/`

`bunfig.toml` sets the test root. New tests belong next to the file
under test. If `<<TEST_ROOT>>` is `test/`, integration-style tests live
there; co-located unit tests still use the `.test.ts` suffix.

### CI parity

`.github/workflows/ci.yml` runs `bun run check:all` and uploads
`coverage/lcov.info` and `junit.xml`. Local `check:all` failures will
break CI; do not push hoping CI will pass.

### Validation reports

If `<<REPO_NAME>>` is audited via the Agent-Readiness rubric, the user
invokes `/readiness-report` manually from this repo's working directory
inside an interactive `droid` session. Agents do not run the auditor
themselves; they make the repo pass.

